3. Scope of License Application
================================================================================

- Directories `textbook/`, `quizzes/`, `exercises/`, `slides/`, `cases/` and all non-code files within them are subject to CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.
- Directory `code/` and any `.v`, `.vhd`, `.sv` hardware description language source files are subject to the MIT License.
- Core IP explicitly marked with `@core-ip` in enterprise-contributed cases is protected by the Enterprise Contributor Agreement and is exempt from the ShareAlike clause of CC BY-NC-SA.

================================================================================
4. Supplementary Clarification for NonCommercial (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)
================================================================================

To avoid ambiguity, the following scenarios are defined:

- Classroom teaching by instructors using this textbook: ✅ Permitted (non-commercial educational purpose)
- Personal study and assignment completion by students: ✅ Permitted (non-commercial purpose)
- Internal copying/distribution by non-profit educational institutions: ✅ Permitted (no commercial profit)
- Charging students fees beyond printing costs when using this textbook as a required text: ❌ Prohibited (exceeding cost is commercial)
- Use by commercial training institutions for internal training: ❌ Prohibited (contact us for dual licensing)
- Formal publication (with ISBN) by a publisher: ❌ Prohibited (requires separate authorization; cooperation already established, other publishers welcome to inquire)

================================================================================
5. Enterprise Contributor Protection (Core IP Exemption)
================================================================================

If an enterprise contributes a case containing core intellectual property (IP), add the `@core-ip` marker at the beginning of the file and sign the Enterprise Contributor Agreement. Such marked content is NOT subject to the ShareAlike clause of CC BY-NC-SA. Third parties may not extract, copy, or reverse-engineer that portion for commercial purposes.

